00:33:28.140 --> 00:33:28.640
Yeah.

00:33:31.814 --> 00:33:33.480
AUDIENCE: So I've
actually been thinking

00:33:33.480 --> 00:33:35.110
about a lot of these
issues for a long time.

00:33:35.110 --> 00:33:37.651
I have a 3-and-1/2-year-old and
I've been trying to introduce

00:33:37.651 --> 00:33:42.680
her to things that I,
as an overprotected kid,

00:33:42.680 --> 00:33:46.652
wasn't able to do until much
later but I feel like she can.

00:33:46.652 --> 00:33:48.110
What I've been
trying to figure out

00:33:48.110 --> 00:33:50.390
is kind of at what
ages to do what things.

00:33:50.390 --> 00:33:53.010
And it feels like a
lot of the resources,

00:33:53.010 --> 00:33:55.520
especially on the
internet-- ugh--

00:33:55.520 --> 00:33:59.527
in America for
determining when is

00:33:59.527 --> 00:34:01.860
a reasonable safe time where,
like you said, five or six

00:34:01.860 --> 00:34:02.390
for fire.

00:34:07.620 --> 00:34:09.620
Can you recommend any
resources for figuring out

00:34:09.620 --> 00:34:13.110
how much earlier than the
American very conservative

00:34:13.110 --> 00:34:16.340
norms different
things could be moved?

00:34:16.340 --> 00:34:18.659
SARA ZASKE: Well, I'm
really reluctant to say

00:34:18.659 --> 00:34:22.389
that any specific age is
good for a specific task.

00:34:22.389 --> 00:34:25.370
It's really important to see
when your kid is ready for it.

00:34:25.370 --> 00:34:27.040
And often, they'll tell you.

00:34:27.040 --> 00:34:29.830
You can suggest some things, and
they'll be like, ugh, no way.

00:34:29.830 --> 00:34:33.139
And I don't recommend forcing
a kid who's reluctant.

00:34:33.139 --> 00:34:37.792
If you wanted to start with
cutting up potatoes together

00:34:37.792 --> 00:34:40.000
and they don't want to touch
the knife, I would wait.

00:34:40.000 --> 00:34:41.110
They'll come back.

00:34:41.110 --> 00:34:44.290
And I'll tell you a short story
about my son in the first time

00:34:44.290 --> 00:34:46.150
he wanted to walk to school.

00:34:46.150 --> 00:34:49.030
He was 6, and we
were in America.

00:34:49.030 --> 00:34:51.280
And he actually
wanted to walk home.

00:34:51.280 --> 00:34:52.239
I had driven that day.

00:34:52.239 --> 00:34:54.670
And he had no interest
in getting in the car.

00:34:54.670 --> 00:34:57.149
And that first time
he ran the whole way.

00:34:57.149 --> 00:34:58.892
And he was scared.

00:34:58.892 --> 00:35:01.350
He didn't really tell me he
was scared, but I kind of knew.

00:35:01.350 --> 00:35:04.630
And then he didn't ask again
for two or three weeks.

00:35:04.630 --> 00:35:06.610
Then when he did
it the second time,

00:35:06.610 --> 00:35:08.240
that's when it clicked for him.

00:35:08.240 --> 00:35:10.430
And today, he
walks all the time.

00:35:10.430 --> 00:35:13.260
So I would think suggesting
some things your kids

00:35:13.260 --> 00:35:14.740
and see if they're into it.

00:35:14.740 --> 00:35:16.780
And then if they
go for it, yeah.

00:35:16.780 --> 00:35:20.410
But if they don't, back off.

00:35:20.410 --> 00:35:23.680
Walking to school, the Germans
do it at about seven and eight.

00:35:23.680 --> 00:35:27.090
The Fins do it at four and five.

00:35:27.090 --> 00:35:30.366
So it's kind of a
cultural thing as well.

00:35:30.366 --> 00:35:33.320
AUDIENCE: Do you have any
thoughts, observations of how

00:35:33.320 --> 00:35:35.750
Germans teach responsibility?

00:35:35.750 --> 00:35:38.350
So for example, you give an
example of kindergarten--

00:35:38.350 --> 00:35:39.100
just play all day.

00:35:39.100 --> 00:35:41.800
But do they get taught
like cleaning up.

00:35:41.800 --> 00:35:43.530
It's not a very
natural consequence,

00:35:43.530 --> 00:35:44.980
like dirty clothes.

00:35:44.980 --> 00:35:47.439
So just wondering what your
thoughts are and observations--

00:35:47.439 --> 00:35:48.146
SARA ZASKE: Sure.

00:35:48.146 --> 00:35:49.720
AUDIENCE: If there's
any differences.

00:35:49.720 --> 00:35:51.650
SARA ZASKE: It was
fairly freeform.

00:35:51.650 --> 00:35:54.430
The kindergarten we went
to had very few rules

00:35:54.430 --> 00:35:56.761
that the kids didn't
make themselves.

00:35:56.761 --> 00:35:58.510
So they actually would
sit the kids around

00:35:58.510 --> 00:36:00.760
and go, what should be the
rules for our [GERMAN]..

00:36:00.760 --> 00:36:03.329
And one kid will say, don't
climb on the furniture.

00:36:03.329 --> 00:36:04.870
And she'd say, why
don't you do that?

00:36:04.870 --> 00:36:07.190
She's like, I don't want
your dirty feet on it.

00:36:07.190 --> 00:36:09.724
Or don't hit other kids.

00:36:09.724 --> 00:36:11.140
Well, that's a
really natural one.

00:36:11.140 --> 00:36:11.640
Why?

00:36:11.640 --> 00:36:12.510
Because it hurts.

00:36:12.510 --> 00:36:14.800
The second answer is
always the most powerful.

00:36:14.800 --> 00:36:17.710
Other kids won't want
to play with you.

00:36:17.710 --> 00:36:19.570
So they learn some
responsibility

00:36:19.570 --> 00:36:21.935
just through the
interaction with each other.

00:36:21.935 --> 00:36:24.190
Now, if you're thinking
our parental interactions

00:36:24.190 --> 00:36:26.410
with them, all
this responsibility

00:36:26.410 --> 00:36:28.720
is rescindable, this freedom.

00:36:28.720 --> 00:36:33.430
So if they are being allowed
to walk to school and instead

00:36:33.430 --> 00:36:35.827
on the way home they
stop at a friend's house,

00:36:35.827 --> 00:36:37.660
then you say, OK, then
maybe we need to take

00:36:37.660 --> 00:36:39.070
a break from it for a while.

00:36:39.070 --> 00:36:41.710
And I think kids,
in that sense, they

00:36:41.710 --> 00:36:44.662
get a little bit of freedom and
then the accountability for it.

00:36:44.662 --> 00:36:46.120
So that when they're
older, they're

00:36:46.120 --> 00:36:50.350
not just going out
there and going crazy.

