00:37:33.070 --> 00:37:37.430
And they have that
connotation on it forever.

00:37:37.430 --> 00:37:40.930
So I would urge you not to
force them to eat anything.

00:37:40.930 --> 00:37:45.760
I'm always a big fan
of continuing to offer.

00:37:45.760 --> 00:37:48.390
You only put out on the table
what you want them to eat.

00:37:48.390 --> 00:37:50.920
But then he gets to
choose from that.

00:37:50.920 --> 00:37:54.190
And of course, the sweets
are only for treats and not

00:37:54.190 --> 00:37:56.170
for all the time.

00:37:56.170 --> 00:37:58.840
The Germans do this a little
bit just through the way

00:37:58.840 --> 00:37:59.920
they do school lunches.

00:37:59.920 --> 00:38:01.540
Nobody brings their own lunch.

00:38:01.540 --> 00:38:04.730
So they have two choices
usually, a vegetarian

00:38:04.730 --> 00:38:06.360
and a non-vegetarian.

00:38:06.360 --> 00:38:09.010
And if you don't like
it, you go hungry.

00:38:09.010 --> 00:38:11.896
So kids tend to eat
if they're hungry.

00:38:11.896 --> 00:38:13.270
AUDIENCE: Thank
you for the talk.

00:38:13.270 --> 00:38:15.780
This is actually really nice.

00:38:15.780 --> 00:38:18.560
My question is-- so if you
look at culture around here

00:38:18.560 --> 00:38:19.150
in the US.

00:38:19.150 --> 00:38:22.220
So for example, there was
a movie [INAUDIBLE] called

00:38:22.220 --> 00:38:24.289
"Kidnap" with Halle Berry.

00:38:24.289 --> 00:38:25.205
SARA ZASKE: Ugh, yeah.

00:38:25.205 --> 00:38:26.270
AUDIENCE: It was
on accord of her

00:38:26.270 --> 00:38:27.870
taking her eyes off
her kid for a second

00:38:27.870 --> 00:38:28.953
and the kid got kidnapped.

00:38:28.953 --> 00:38:33.150
And then [INAUDIBLE]
and all that stuff.

00:38:33.150 --> 00:38:35.490
My question is-- so if
I see a movie like that,

00:38:35.490 --> 00:38:38.780
I'm less reluctant to
let my kid walk to school

00:38:38.780 --> 00:38:42.090
or lay on the playground
unsupervised for a second.

00:38:42.090 --> 00:38:46.140
So how do you reconcile with
an environment like that?

00:38:46.140 --> 00:38:48.360
Because I'm assuming,
like in Germany,

00:38:48.360 --> 00:38:51.080
they have a lot more control
over their media, or at least

00:38:51.080 --> 00:38:53.882
that's the perception
that I have being here

00:38:53.882 --> 00:38:57.220
that they can prevent movies
like this from coming out.

00:38:57.220 --> 00:38:59.665
Saying, hey, don't
show things like this.

00:38:59.665 --> 00:39:02.370
[INAUDIBLE] kids walk
to school on their own.

00:39:02.370 --> 00:39:03.840
So how do we reconcile this?

00:39:03.840 --> 00:39:04.810
Thank you.

00:39:04.810 --> 00:39:06.810
SARA ZASKE: It is a
different media environment.

00:39:06.810 --> 00:39:10.180
I don't know that they
control it so much.

00:39:10.180 --> 00:39:12.870
But there would not be as much
interest in that kind of movie.

00:39:12.870 --> 00:39:15.460
We like to scare
ourselves a lot here.

00:39:15.460 --> 00:39:17.300
What I really wish would
happen in our media

00:39:17.300 --> 00:39:19.500
is that, whenever
they tell us one

00:39:19.500 --> 00:39:21.640
of the real stories of
a kid being kidnapped

00:39:21.640 --> 00:39:23.520
that they put it in context.

00:39:23.520 --> 00:39:25.200
And as a formal
journalist, I wish

00:39:25.200 --> 00:39:27.366
we could require this because
you're always supposed

00:39:27.366 --> 00:39:29.070
to put things in context.

00:39:29.070 --> 00:39:31.830
A little more than
100 kids get kidnapped

00:39:31.830 --> 00:39:33.540
by strangers every year.

00:39:33.540 --> 00:39:36.060
Absolutely every
story is horrific.

00:39:36.060 --> 00:39:38.230
It's every parent's nightmare.

00:39:38.230 --> 00:39:41.430
But we have 77 million
kids in this country.

00:39:41.430 --> 00:39:45.120
Something happening to 100
kids is an aberration, not

00:39:45.120 --> 00:39:47.440
a thing that happens every day.

00:39:47.440 --> 00:39:51.280
And if we knew that, if we
keep thinking about that,

00:39:51.280 --> 00:39:53.160
I think we might
change our behavior.

00:39:53.160 --> 00:39:55.890
And one other short
story if I may.

00:39:55.890 --> 00:39:59.460
The far more common scenario
of a kid being sexually abused

00:39:59.460 --> 00:40:01.240
is by someone they know.

00:40:01.240 --> 00:40:02.970
And it's usually a man.

00:40:02.970 --> 00:40:06.190
And that man wants to have a
relationship with your child.

00:40:06.190 --> 00:40:08.810
Now, the child that has
been very constrained

00:40:08.810 --> 00:40:11.520
and told to obey adults and
respect their elders all

00:40:11.520 --> 00:40:15.330
the time is much easier
prey to a person like that

00:40:15.330 --> 00:40:17.750
than a kid who's been
raised to be independent,

00:40:17.750 --> 00:40:19.290
is able to say no to adults.

00:40:19.290 --> 00:40:20.820
So there's a really
strong argument

00:40:20.820 --> 00:40:23.250
right there for making
your kid more independent

00:40:23.250 --> 00:40:24.995
actually protects them.

00:40:24.995 --> 00:40:28.303
AUDIENCE: OK, I come from a
slightly different perspective.

00:40:28.303 --> 00:40:34.400
[GERMAN] So as you
see, I'm from Germany.

00:40:34.400 --> 00:40:37.810
And when we moved
here, the school system

00:40:37.810 --> 00:40:43.270
here does not really like if
your kids have these values

00:40:43.270 --> 00:40:45.060
that you propagate here.

00:40:45.060 --> 00:40:50.240
So for your own
children and in general,

00:40:50.240 --> 00:40:52.012
how do you propose
that the school

00:40:52.012 --> 00:40:55.825
system and this
kind of education

00:40:55.825 --> 00:40:57.210
really works together?

00:40:57.210 --> 00:41:03.240
Because for our kids,
it's very interesting.

00:41:03.240 --> 00:41:05.900
So for example, things like
the Pledge of Allegiance

00:41:05.900 --> 00:41:07.200
in elementary school.

00:41:07.200 --> 00:41:10.152
This was pretty scary
from my perspective.

00:41:10.152 --> 00:41:17.930
But all this value on secondary
virtues like being on time,

00:41:17.930 --> 00:41:21.080
having all your work
done and, well, all

00:41:21.080 --> 00:41:24.210
this control that you mentioned
that does not really go well

00:41:24.210 --> 00:41:27.300
with this style of education.

00:41:27.300 --> 00:41:31.110
SARA ZASKE: I've handled it
a couple of different ways.

00:41:31.110 --> 00:41:34.350
I've had teachers who are
receptive to it and schools

00:41:34.350 --> 00:41:34.860
that are.

00:41:34.860 --> 00:41:37.950
I tell them my kids
are allowed to go home.

00:41:37.950 --> 00:41:39.360
Sometimes I have
to write a note,

00:41:39.360 --> 00:41:42.025
because we're a very
litigious culture, saying

00:41:42.025 --> 00:41:44.730
that they have my permission
to do these things.

00:41:44.730 --> 00:41:47.330
And sometimes I get a
little passive aggressive.

00:41:47.330 --> 00:41:49.470
I have a teacher--

00:41:49.470 --> 00:41:52.650
kids do not need to do
homework in elementary school.

00:41:52.650 --> 00:41:54.900
I'll say that there are
no grades, especially

00:41:54.900 --> 00:41:57.360
until third grade.

00:41:57.360 --> 00:42:00.000
And there's no proof
that doing homework

00:42:00.000 --> 00:42:02.430
helps in elementary school.

00:42:02.430 --> 00:42:05.670
And I have had arguments
with teachers about this.

00:42:05.670 --> 00:42:09.750
And other times, I've just
said to my son, don't do it.

00:42:09.750 --> 00:42:11.269
You don't have to
do the homework.

00:42:11.269 --> 00:42:12.810
And if you want to
do it and you want

00:42:12.810 --> 00:42:14.400
to bring me the
little piece of paper

00:42:14.400 --> 00:42:15.885
that I'm supposed
to sign, which is

00:42:15.885 --> 00:42:19.029
a really interesting transfer
of responsibility, you can.

00:42:19.029 --> 00:42:20.820
And the moment he does
that, he'll probably

00:42:20.820 --> 00:42:22.950
have passed some bar.

00:42:22.950 --> 00:42:25.940
But I don't let them
make me control him.

00:42:25.940 --> 00:42:26.950
Does that make sense?

00:42:26.950 --> 00:42:27.491
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:42:27.491 --> 00:42:29.428
SARA ZASKE: Yeah.

00:42:29.428 --> 00:42:31.327
Any other questions?

00:42:31.327 --> 00:42:33.410
AUDIENCE: Do you have any
theories on how American

00:42:33.410 --> 00:42:35.108
culture developed this way?

00:42:35.108 --> 00:42:35.816
SARA ZASKE: Yeah.

00:42:35.816 --> 00:42:38.900
Unfortunately, I
only have theories.

00:42:38.900 --> 00:42:42.350
A lot of it is the media
and those scary stories

00:42:42.350 --> 00:42:43.280
and scary movies.

00:42:43.280 --> 00:42:44.585
I mean, we have a show.

00:42:44.585 --> 00:42:46.130
I think it's called
"Law and Order--

00:42:46.130 --> 00:42:49.370
Special Victims Unit"
where every week a child

00:42:49.370 --> 00:42:51.800
is in some horrific situation.

00:42:51.800 --> 00:42:56.480
And it gives the impression
that this happens often.

00:42:56.480 --> 00:42:58.820
I also think that we have
a very competitive culture

00:42:58.820 --> 00:43:00.110
and always have.

00:43:00.110 --> 00:43:02.990
So we are so worried
about our kids' success

00:43:02.990 --> 00:43:06.980
that we think we need to start
them on that treadmill early.

00:43:06.980 --> 00:43:11.510
And it's actually had
some very bad results.

00:43:11.510 --> 00:43:13.101
Because if you're
a kid and you're

00:43:13.101 --> 00:43:15.350
working really hard in
kindergarten and in first grade

00:43:15.350 --> 00:43:17.330
so that you can work really
hard in middle school

00:43:17.330 --> 00:43:19.100
and high school so you can
get into a good college

00:43:19.100 --> 00:43:21.724
and worked really hard to get a
good job so you can work really

00:43:21.724 --> 00:43:24.170
hard, that can be
very depressing and

00:43:24.170 --> 00:43:26.080
anxiety-producing.

00:43:26.080 --> 00:43:28.820
Where is the moment
for enjoyment

00:43:28.820 --> 00:43:31.370
and the meaning of life really?

00:43:31.370 --> 00:43:35.630
Is it just to constantly compete
and be the best and make money?

00:43:35.630 --> 00:43:38.680
Or is there something else
there that's of value?

00:43:38.680 --> 00:43:41.150
And I think if we
change our view on that

00:43:41.150 --> 00:43:42.830
and how we communicate
with our kids,

00:43:42.830 --> 00:43:46.370
it could help them out a lot.

00:43:46.370 --> 00:43:49.130
OK, should we break
at this point?

00:43:49.130 --> 00:43:50.615
SPEAKER 1: Any more questions?

00:43:50.615 --> 00:43:52.330
AUDIENCE: What's in the book?

00:43:52.330 --> 00:43:53.761
SARA ZASKE: What's in the book?

00:43:53.761 --> 00:43:55.980
Some of those
stories I told here.

00:43:55.980 --> 00:43:58.410
It's a research
memoir, so it's partly

00:43:58.410 --> 00:44:00.100
my stories and experiences.

00:44:00.100 --> 00:44:02.280
And it's partly I talked
to a lot of experts

00:44:02.280 --> 00:44:03.780
and looked at studies as well.

00:44:03.780 --> 00:44:05.475
And I would say
it's part manifesto

00:44:05.475 --> 00:44:08.340
because I'm trying to make an
argument that we should give

00:44:08.340 --> 00:44:11.725
our kids more independence.

00:44:11.725 --> 00:44:13.350
SPEAKER 1: Thanks
for coming everybody.

00:44:13.350 --> 00:44:16.700
[APPLAUSE]

